*Proof of Theorem <a href="#t:JitomirskayaSimon:refl" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="t:JitomirskayaSimon:refl">2</a>.* Assume $\alpha$ is $B$-reflective and $B$ is sufficiently large. Choose $|\zeta_i| \to \infty$ such that $\alpha$ is $(B,\zeta_i)$-reflective. By passing to a subsequence, we may assume that every $\zeta_i$ has the same sign and $2\zeta_i$ has the same residue modulo $4$ for every $i$. Without loss of generality, we consider the case $\zeta_i>0$ and $2\zeta_i \cong 2 \ \mathrm{mod} \ 4$ for every $i$, so we write $\zeta_i = 2m_i- 1$ with $m_i \in {\mathbb{N}}$. The other cases are similar. The main difference between the cases is what transfer matrix cocycle one must use. To be concrete, the current case compares $N$ with its “reflected” variant, while the case $2\zeta_i \cong 0 \ \mathrm{mod} \ 4$ compares $M$ with its reflected variant. The case of half-integer centers ($2\zeta_i$ odd) requires one to use transfer matrices associated with the *transpose* of a CMV matrix, but aside from that, all steps are analogous.

Due to , it suffices to prove the statement of the theorem for a single admissible $\rho$. As discussed in Remark <a href="#rem:symmForRhoFromAlpha" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="rem:symmForRhoFromAlpha">12</a>, the symmetry of the $\alpha_n$ can be passed to $\rho_n$, and furthermore, we need $\rho$ to satisfy bounds such as <a href="#eq:rhosymm" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:rhosymm">[eq:rhosymm]</a> (up to shifting the center of reflection). Thus, we choose $\rho_n= i\sqrt{1-|\alpha_n|^2}$. Consequently, we may assume henceforth that $$\label{eq:assump}
        |\rho_{4m_i- \ell-2}+\overline{\rho_\ell}| \lesssim  e^{-B\zeta_i},\qquad |\alpha_{4m_i-\ell-2}-\overline{\alpha_\ell}|<e^{-B\zeta_i},$$ for every $\ell \in {\mathbb{Z}}$ satisfying $|\zeta_i-\ell| \leq e^{B\zeta_i}$, and recall that our assumptions give $|\rho_\ell | \geq c_0>0$ uniformly in $\ell \in {\mathbb{Z}}$.

<div class="remark">

**Remark 13**. By a standard telescoping estimate, <a href="#eq:assump" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:assump">[eq:assump]</a> implies that (since $|\rho|,|\alpha|\leq1$) $$\begin{aligned}
        |\alpha_{4m_i-\ell-2}\rho_{4m_i-\ell'-2}+\overline{\alpha_\ell}\overline{\rho_{\ell'}}|
        & \lesssim   e^{-B\zeta_i}

\end{aligned}$$ for all $\ell,\ell' \in {\mathbb{Z}}$ with $|\zeta_i-\ell|, |\zeta_i-\ell'| \leq e^{B\zeta_i}$, with similar bounds for other suitable combinations of $\rho$’s and $\alpha$’s.

</div>

Let us define the reflection of $u$ through $2m_i-\tfrac12$ by $$\label{eq:ui}
    u_i(k) = u(4m_i-k-1)$$ and note that $$u_i(2n-1)=u(4m_i-2n),\qquad u_i(2n)=u(4m_i-2n-1).$$

